1 Introduction

This is a description of the workflow for qaLabel, which applies QA labels to each observation in a CyTOF dataset.

library(qaLabel)
library(ggplot2)

2 Read in data and create initial datasets

The function read in the data and formats a that contains all of the QA variables. The variables are renamed so that their names can be easily accessed by downstream functions. The help file specifies how to do this. The Gaussian parameters and event length are transformed with the function. The output is a .

fname <- "../../data/Sarah_data/U2OS_NT-1_GFP_Spike_NORMAL_01_1.fcs"
tech <- dataPrep(fname,
                 time = "Time", 
                 beads = c("Beads"), 
                 dna = c("DNA1", "DNA2"), 
                 event_length = "Event_length", 
                 viability = "Viability")
head(tech)

The function creates a that contains the labels and information about the labels. It is built using the dataset. The first variable is the label and each observation is assigned a label of either cell or GDPzero. The GDPzero label is assigned to any variable that has a 0 for any of the GDP variables. The has variables for beads, doublets, debris, and viability. The values for those variables are initially set to NA. The purpose of this dataset is to iteratively change the label for the observations and assign probabilities to each observation in regard its status as a bead, doublet, debris, or live/dead cell.

labels <- qaDataFrame(tech)
head(labels)
#>     Time label bead doublet debris dead

#> 6 40.169  cell   NA      NA     NA   NA
table(labels$label)

#>    cell GDPzero 
#>  235185   12428

3 Nearest neighbors

The next piece in the process is finding the nearest neighbors for each of the observations. There are currently two choices: k-means nearest neighbors and mutual nearest neighbors. This piece only needs to be done once.

# K-means nearest neighbors
knn <- NN(tech, n = 10, type = "knn")
head(knn)
dim(knn)

# Mutual nearest neighbors
mnn <- NN(tech, n = 20, type = "mnn")

4 Beads

4.1 Initial bead labeling

The beads are typically the first type of observation that should be labeled. The beads should separate clearly from the non-beads. The first step is to obtain initial labels for the beads. This is done with the function. The function returns a that contains the bead assignment for each bead channel and a final bead designation in the variable called init.

beads <- initialBead(tech, labels)
head(beads)
#>     Time Bead1  init
#> 1  6.719 FALSE FALSE
#> 2 13.034 FALSE FALSE
#> 3 13.685 FALSE FALSE
#> 4 19.089 FALSE FALSE
#> 5 25.768 FALSE FALSE
#> 6 40.169 FALSE FALSE
sum(beads$init)
#> [1] 19284

The function can be used to visualize the data with regard to a grouping variable. This allows us to see what is classified as beads in the original bead data.

cytofHist(x = tech[, "Bead1"], group = beads$init, "Bead channel")

The zeros make it difficult to see the trends, so here are the plots without the zeros. The density option was also used to emphasize the smaller group.

cytofHist(x = tech[, "Bead1"], group = beads$init, type = "density", 
          title = "Bead channel")

4.2 Find mismatches

This next part identifies the observations that are mismatched from its neighbors in regard to bead assignment using the nearest neighbors matrix. If an observation is a designated as a bead, its nearest neighbors that are also beads are assigned a value of FALSE. If a neighbor is not a bead, it is given a value of TRUe, indicating that it is a mismatch of the observation. The rows are then summed together and rows with one or more TRUE values are designated as mismatches. The function returns nearest neighbors matrix with values of TRUE/FALSE as values indicating the mismatch status and a variable called Mismatch that is TRUE if the observation is a mismatch and FALSE if it is not.

This is a piece that we are not very happy with at this time. It selects only points that are hard to classify, which means that we are building a labeling model only with points that we are not very certain about. We plan to change this soon.

mm <- mismatch(mnn, beads$init, threshold = 1)
head(mm)

#> 5 25.768 FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

4.3 Create a subset of data to make a model with

We plan to create a model using a smaller set of data. This next piece selects a subset of data points to build the model with. Only the points selected by the previous piece (currently the mismatches) are considered to be in this subset. If no points are designated as mismatches, as is the case with the beads, the entire set of unclassified data points (those that still have a cell label) is sampled. The data are sampled at random, but weighted to ensure we have a fairly balanced dataset to build the labeling model with. The function returns a set of indices that identifies the points in the dataset that will be used to compute the labeling model.

ind <- modelData(labels, subset = mm$Mismatch, init = beads$init, n = 4000)
length(ind)
#> [1] 4000
head(ind)
#> [1] 222297  15874 218330  57951 128446 227994

The following histogram shows where the selected points are relative to the rest of the points for each of the bead channels.

index <- rep(FALSE, nrow(tech))
index[ind] <- TRUE
cytofHist(x = tech[, "Bead1"], group = index, type = "density", 
          title = "Bead channel")

4.4 Final classification of beads

There are currently three models that can be used to classify the beads: support vector machines, random forests, and gradient boosting machines. The method below uses random forests, but the process is identical for SVMs and GBMs. The function for svm and gbm are and . The labeling functions take the same input and produce identical ouput. The output is a that is identical to the but with the beads labeled as beads and the predicted probability of being a bead assigned to each observation in the bead variable. This is the labels that should be used for the next step because the bead label is needed for all other QA labels.

rf.labs <- rfLabel(tech, labels, type = "bead", init = beads$init, index = ind)
head(rf.labs)
#>     Time label  bead doublet debris dead
#> 1  6.719  cell 0.000      NA     NA   NA
#> 2 13.034  cell 0.000      NA     NA   NA
#> 3 13.685  cell 0.000      NA     NA   NA
#> 4 19.089  cell 0.004      NA     NA   NA
#> 5 25.768  cell 0.000      NA     NA   NA
#> 6 40.169  cell 0.002      NA     NA   NA
table(rf.labs$label)
#> 
#>    bead    cell GDPzero 
#>   19338  215847   12428

These are the plots with the zeros removed

tmp <- data.frame(bead = tech[, "Bead1"], group = rf.labs$label)
tmp <- tmp[tmp$bead > 0, ]
cytofHist(tmp$bead, group = tmp$group, type = "count", title = "Bead channel")

5 Doublets

This bit labels the doublets. It has the exact same structure as the beads. Note that the updated label should be used because the bead labels are needed for each of the steps.

5.1 Initial doublet labeling

The doublets are difficult to classify and we compute a doubletScore to classify them. There are currently three options for classifying the doublet. They are selected using the score argument and they are documented in the help file for . The function returns the doublet score, the group it was assigned to, and the initial doublet classification in the init variable.

doublets <- initialDoublet(tech, rf.labs, score = 1)
#> [1] "removing 1"
#> [1] "removing 2"
head(doublets)
#>     Time doubletScore doubletGroup  init
#> 1  6.719   0.81483725            1 FALSE
#> 2 13.034   0.87867355            1 FALSE
#> 3 13.685   0.09095377            1 FALSE
#> 4 19.089   1.25380547            1 FALSE
#> 5 25.768   0.14394249            1 FALSE
#> 6 40.169  -0.27694356            1 FALSE

This shows a classification of the doublet scores for the unclassified points (all of those still labeled cell). The scores for the classified points can be seen on the histogram by selection .

cytofHist(doublets$doubletScore, doublets$doubletGroup, na.rm = TRUE, 
          title = "Doublet score and initial classification")

d.rf.index <- modelData(rf.labs, subset = dm$Mismatch, init = doublets$init, n = 4000)

The following histogram shows where the selected points are relative to the rest of the doublet scores.

index <- rep("All", nrow(tech))

          title = "Doublet subset")

6 Debris

This bit labels the debris. It has the exact same structure as the beads. Note that the updated label should be used because the previous labels are needed for this step.

6.1 Initial debris labeling

The debris are difficult to classify and we compute a debrisScore to classify them. There are currently three options for classifying debris. They are selected using the score argument and they are documented in the help file for . The function returns the debris score, the group it was assigned to, and the initial debris classification in the init variable.

debris <- initialDebris(tech, rf.labs, score = 1)
head(debris)

This is a umap of the different labels. the umap was created using the standardized tech data.

s.tech <- scale(tech[, -1])
lab.umap <- uwot::umap(s.tech, ret_model = TRUE)
lab.umapD <- data.frame(x = lab.umap$embedding[, 1], y = lab.umap$embedding[, 2])
g.dat <- CATALYST::prepData(fname)
gfp <- g.dat@assays@data$exprs[rownames(g.dat@assays@data$exprs) == "GFP", ]
vericells <- g.dat@assays@data$exprs[rownames(g.dat@assays@data$exprs) == "VeriCells", ]


umapData <- data.frame(lab.umapD, labels = rf.labs$label)
umapData$bead <- ifelse(rf.labs$label == "bead", "Bead", "Not-Bead")
umapData$doublet <- ifelse(rf.labs$label == "doublet", "Doublet", "Not-Doublet")
umapData$debris <- ifelse(rf.labs$label == "debris", "Debris", "Not-Debris")
umapData$GDPzero <- ifelse(rf.labs$label == "GDPzero", "GDPzero", "Not-GDPzero")
umapData$cell <- ifelse(rf.labs$label == "cell", "Cells", "Not-Cells")
umapData$gfp <- log(gfp)
umapData$vericells <- vericells

umapData$labels <- factor(umapData$labels, levels = c("cell", "GDPzero", "bead", "doublet", "debris"))
require(RColorBrewer)
cols <- brewer.pal(5, "Set2")
umapG <- ggplot(umapData, aes(x = x, y = y, color = labels)) + 
  geom_point(size = 0.25) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = cols) +
  labs(title = "Random forest", x = "", y = "") +
  guides(colour = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 3))) +
  theme_bw()
